    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-11-09T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-11-09T23:00:00-05:00" n="254"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d254">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/11290: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-11-10T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 10, 1930—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received November 10—6:45
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>112. The following telegram has been sent to the Legation: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“November 10, noon. Steamship <hi rend="italic">Ifung</hi> and lighter
                            No. 1, both of Yangtze Rapid Company, fired upon at three different
                            places by trench mortars and rifles on Saturday<note n="14"
                                xml:id="d254fn14">November 8.</note> between Chenglingki and Ichang.
                            American naval guard on <hi rend="italic">Ifung</hi> returned fire in
                            each case <pb facs="0311" n="213" xml:id="pg_213"/> of attack on that
                            vessel. Resumption of through passenger traffic between Hankow and
                            Peiping announced by Railway Administration effective today. This marks
                            first through train service between Hankow and Peiping since
                            approximately March 15, 1930. Repeated to the Department.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
